        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-03-14 15:41:39.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1\n\nOn the equalsIgnoreCase, we're checking against these constants:\nString modelNamePropertyKey = \"model-ver.model-name\";\nString modelVersionPropertyKey = \"model-ver.model-version\";\nString modelVersionIdPropertyKey = \"model-ver.model-version-id\"\n\nMy view would be that if the field name does not match the constant keys exactly then it's an error somewhere; the constants are a check that the message is correct. I think therefore that \"equals()\" and not \"equalsIgnoreCase()\" is perferable.",
        "patchset_number": 3
      },
      {
        "id": "ab2b85e49ca4f51369981b0993645a1ecfc9424e",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 57,
          "name": "Pamela Dragosh",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "pd1248@att.com",
          "username": "pdragosh"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-03-14 15:45:16.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2\n\nOk that makes sense. Ideally A&AI should not change field names, especially if they must be backward compatible with their API version.",
        "patchset_number": 3
      },
